Fiduciary obligations represent the most stringent standards of care recognized by the United States legal system. At a post-graduate level, analyzing fiduciary law requires moving past basic definitions to examine the foundational tension: optimizing economic efficiency while mitigating severe agency costs.Jurisprudential FoundationsAmerican fiduciary law operates as a gap-filling mechanism for incomplete contracts.The Contractarian View: Led by Easterbrook and Fischel, this theory posits that fiduciary duties are simply the default terms that parties would have bargained for if transaction costs were zero. Obligations are fundamentally waivable.The Anti-Contractarian (Moralist) View: Championed by scholars like Tamar Frankel, this view argues that fiduciary duties are status-based and socially imposed. They reflect public policy boundaries that cannot be contracted away.The Dual Core Pillars                     ┌──────────────────────────────┐
