1. The Duty of CareThe duty of care requires fiduciaries to manage assets with the skill and diligence of an ordinarily prudent person under similar circumstances.The Business Judgment Rule (BJR): In corporate law, the BJR creates a rebuttable presumption that directors act on an informed basis, in good faith, and in the honest belief that the action taken was in the best interests of the company.Judicial Deference: Courts will not second-guess a business decision—even a disastrous one—unless the presumption is rebutted by showing fraud, bad faith, or gross negligence in the decision-making process (see Smith v. Van Gorkom, 488 A.2d 858 (Del. 1985)).2. The Duty of LoyaltyThe duty of loyalty is absolute and uncompromising. As Justice Benjamin Cardozo famously articulated in Meinhard v. Salmon, 164 N.E. 545 (N.Y. 1928), a fiduciary is held to "something stricter than the morals of the market place. Not honesty alone, but the punctilio of an honor the most sensitive..."The No-Further-Inquiry Rule: In trust law, if a trustee engages in self-dealing, the transaction is voidable at the beneficiary's option. Courts do not inquire into whether the transaction was fair or if the trust suffered harm.Corporate Opportunity Doctrine: Corporate insiders cannot usurp a business opportunity that falls within the corporation’s line of business unless the corporation is given the first right of refusal and rejects it.Systemic Variations Across Asset Paradigms┌──────────────────┬─────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┐
